commentText: Just so people know a lie detector isn't always right. There is a scene in the show Lie to Me, where the head of the company explains to some people developing a hand held lie detector. That it's about as effective as holding an egg, if you were lying the egg would break, because you would start to grip it tighter. However, it wasn't very effective because people would get afraid, angry, nervous, and the egg would break despite them telling the truth. Lie detectors are not detecting lies. It is more accurate to say they are truth verifiers. The machine can't tell you if you're lying but it will show you the comparison between your normal body readings when telling the truth to how your body reacts when you are lying. For this reason, someone who may not be lying but the topic makes them feel uncomfortable or makes them think of something that happened to another person, it may show as "lying". This is why the polygraph examiner will do follow up questions to verify if it is a lie or not.

Lie detectors actually don't test if you're lying or not, they measure your heart rate, perspiration, and nervous system arousal. Basically that means if your heartbeat speeds up just from hearing something like the word murder, the lie detector notices that. Ergo all you have to do to "pass" one of these and make it seem like you're not lying is to already be nervous before the detector begins detecting your emotions and that way it won't come across as anything suspicious if your heartbeat is already fast when it starts. That or some people don't even react to hearing things such as "Did you kill this woman?" This is why innocent people have been incarcerated just because they get nervous from hearing these accusations, or guilty people gone free because they don't react to the accusations.

replies.commentText: It doesn't really, I had to do a research essay about psuedo sciences and most of the time it doesn't work. All it graphs are peoples heart rate, blood pressure, breathing, and how much a person is sweating. People can also take classes to learn how to trick polygraph tests. In the 1960's a polygraph expert tried the test on a plant and got reads off of it so he concluded that plants have emotions, instead of doing the sane thing and saying the test doesn't actually work. There are lots of facts backing up that it doesn't work, these are only some of them.
yep...I knew it

Random person on the internet. I can tell you for sure it doesn't because my husband took one and lied through his teeth the whole way through and they said he was telling the truth even though we knew it was a lie.

They don't. I believe polygraphs actually aren't admissible in criminal court in most cases because they're not actually "lie detectors", they just measure physical symptoms that often correlate with lies. You can trick a polygraph test with proper training, just like you can fail one just by simply being too nervous.

People's bodies usually react when they lie which is why when you use the device they get a baseline of your heart rate they just ask basic questions and then that pretty much determines how you are when you are not lying which is why when you lie you go off the baseline.  Course people can learn to control the way their body reacts and trick the machine.  People were also known to keep stuff in shoes to stab them so when they answered base questions who would naturally be high so they could lie and wouldn't detect it.  So it isn't fully accurate because you can just be nervous at one point and it will read you are lying even though you are not.  It isn't a magical machine that detects liars it just goes off of physiological signs when people lie.
